{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_ilia_ver01/data/sn87055779/00271740643/1930011901/0315.xml":{"full_text":"SIGNS OF BUSINESS REVIVAL MORE\nGENERAL UPWARD\nTREND SLOW BUT\nON. SOUND BASIS\nI\nRecovery in Steel Output)\nAmong Encouraging\nFactors in Recovery.\nBy W. S. COUSINS,\nI. N. S, Financial Editor\nNEW YORK, Jan. 18.\u2014With more\nthan halt of January already having\npassed, evidences of business revival,\nalthough by no means general, are\nbecoming more numerous. It is hardly\nf to be expected that the pace of the\nrecovery will be other than slow, and\nthat it will be scattered rather than\ngeneral, for in a transition period\nsuch as we are now going through,\nthe normal precedure is for gradual\nand irregular improvement.\nThis has been the experience of\nmost preceding eras of readjustment,\nyet a gradual advance upon a sound\nbasis is more to be desired than a too\nrapid expansion whose duration might\nbe shortened by over-extension. The\npresent process of recuperation from\nthe effects of the late financial un\nsetUement is chiefly visible not in the\nquarter where it had been looked for,\nand the further rise of steel produc\ntion Is especially encouraging at a\ntlm& when such a trend is helpful to\n^entiment.\nSteel Demand Grows\nHowever, the recovery in steel out\njjut, wfilch has carried the average\nJor the principal producers up to\nabout 70 per cent of capacity, con\ntrasts with receding prices. Not since\nJuly, 1928, has the composite quota\ntion for finished steel compiled by the\nIron Age been at the present level,\nthe current week bringing declines in\ntank plates, structural shapes, sheets,\nwire nails and barbed wire. Demand\nlor steel continues to grow, however,\nand it is believed that the recent\ndownward revision of prices has rep\nresented an effort to bring about\ngreater stabilization in the markets.\nA strong supporting force, as it has\nbeen for some time, is the sustained\ncall from railroads, while automobile\nmanufacturers, although taking rela\ntively little steel now. are increasing\ntheir operations. In basic materials,\nfew changes of significance have ap\npeared. There is a gradual better\nment in pig iron business, yet uncer\ntainty about prices in some districts\nhas a restraining effect on new buy\ning.\nTurns Reactionary\nThe stock market after acting buoy\nantly for the forepart of the week has\nonce more turned reactionary, and at\nthe closing session prices were back\nto the plane of the previous week. It\nis becoming more and more evident\nin the present activity of the opposing\n.forces interested in the trend of se\ncurity prices, that no definite move\nment will evolve to the upside until\nunmistakable signs of a clearing away\ni of the present uncertainty in the busi\nness and industrial situation comes to\nlight. At the same time powerful\nbanking interests are guardedly\nwatching that no extended reaction\ntake place to disturb the generally\nimproved sentiment while still in a\nformative state. For the present,\ntherefore, it is hardly to be expected\nthat the market will be other than in\na trading area, especially susceptible\nto the changing whims of the profes\nsional trading clement.\nA further recession has been noted\nIn the employment situation. Both\nfactory mployment and factory pay\nrolls continued to recede rapidly in\nDecember. The decline in employ\nment carried the employment index\ncompiled by the Annalist down to\n97.7 from November figures of 99.6,\nand the decrease in factory wage pay\nments carried the payrolls index\ndown to 96.4 from November figures\n1 of 100.1. The index of factory pay\nrolls for December on the basis of\ndata on hand from this source, a pre\ncisely the lowest level reached in the\nbusiness recession of 1929, which was\n96.4 for November of that year\nRate Drop Is Aid\nFreight car loadings give ro Indi\ncation of changing from the declining\ntrend which has been fohowed for\nsome months. Loadings of rm-enue\nfreight for the week ended on Jan. 4\ntotaled 776,259 cars. Compared with\nthe corresponding week in 1929 this\nwas a reduction of 22,423 cars, but an\nincrease of 22.012 over the correspond\ning week in 1928.\nThe continued general downward\ntendency of the leading European ex\nchange rates during the greater part\nof the week is a favorable item in the\nlocal money situation- Interest rates\nin the leading European financial\ncenters have now fallen to a point\nwhich makes further transfer of metal\nunlikely.\nf- Statistics\nr MARRIAGE LICENSES\nTony Klsmczewski, 19,-717 S. Liber\nty street and Marie Rozek, 20, 2014\nKenwood avenue.\nErnest Miller, 20, 1236 Longfellow\nStreet and Alice Mohn, 20, Misha\nwaka\nHoward Wagner, 24. J21&,Marrietta\nstreet and Miriam Dingman, 25, 718\nOat&lpa street.\nHarold Brownell. 25. Benton Harbor,\nMich., and Edna Sheffield, 19, Benton\nHarbor, Mich.\nWEEKLY COTTON REVIEW\nWj International New* SerTire:\nCHICAGO, Jan. 18\u2014Trade in cot\nton was light'today. Final prices were\nfive points higher to eight lower.\nJanuary closed at $17; March $17.25;\nMay $17.48; July and October $17.62.\nFor the week prices were 20 to 28\npoints lower.\nThe market moved within an ex\ntremely narrow range during the\nweek with outside interest small.\nCsdcles were uneven adn crop news\nmixed Domestic consumption figures\nfor December were smaller than cx\npected.\nU? CLOSING IBERTY BONDS.\nNEW YORK.NJan. 18.\u2014Final trans\nactions in Liberty,tends here today\nhere at the following prices: 3 1-2\u2019s,\n99.8; 4th 41-4\u2019s, 100.31; treasury\n33-8\u2019s, 99.7; treasury 3 3-4\u2019s 103122.\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBy THOMSON-McKINWON.\nA\nOpen High Xi\u00abw Close\nAdr. Rnraely .1 2% 18 1*V4\nA dr. Bain. Fid. WH 26%\nAjax Rubber 2%\nAlleghany ..SS 85\nAllis Chalmers B1 W4 61%\nAmerican Bosch 41% 42% 40* 42%\nAmer. Brake Shoe 47 47\nAmerican Can ....121% 122% 120 122\nAme. Car and Fdy. 80 80\nAmer. For. Power 90 90% 88% 90%\nAmerican Iiocomo. 99% 99%\nAmerican Radia