nSwift and Co. ...134\nSwift Inti.31*\nTJnitd Corp. Pfd. 12\u2019%\nC. S. Gypsum 42\nF. S. B. and Telv. 8\nCtll. Ind. Corp. 18% 18% 17% 18\nDo Pfd. 2574 25% 25 25\nWahl 7%\nZenith 6\n_ 30\n38% 38%\n8% 9\n_ 33\n_ 16\n6% 6%\n2374\n_134\n31% 32%\n1276\n42% 43 42%\n8\n6%\n33\n0%\n7%\n676\nNew York Curb\nMarket\nSKW YORK CURB MARKET.\nBy HARRIS, UPHAM ft CO.\nClosing Quotation!.\nAmerican G. and E.117%\nArkansas National Gas 0%\nAssociated G. and E. 41\nBlue Ridge 7%\nCarib. Syndicate\nCities Service 28%\nColombian Syndicate .5-16\nCons. Ant. Mdsg.\nIleForest 3%\nDurant 4%\nElectric B. and S. 82%\nFord of England 10%\nFourth National 35%\nFoi Theaters \u201cA\u201d 6%\nGoldman Sachs 35%\nGulf Oil .134%.\nHumble Oii 70%.\nInd. Ter. 111. Oil 26%\nJohnson Motors 30\nNla. Hud. Fow. 13%\nDitto A Wts. 3%\nPitney Bowes 11%\nPrudential Investment 15%\nSchulte United 3%\nStandard Oil of Indiana 52%\nStnts Motors 3%\nTampa Electric 77\nTrans-America 43%\nUnited Gas 26\nVacuum .04\nNEW YORK PRODUCE\nNEW YORK. Jan. 18.\u2014Hour, dull\nbut steady; spring patents $6.25@6.75;\npork firm; mess $26.50. Lard steady;\nmiddle west spot $10.85@10.95. Tallow\nfirm; special to extra 7%@7%. Po\ntatoes, quiet and steady; Long Island\n$1.50@6.50; southern $2.50@3.50;.\nMaine $4.35^75.65; Bermunda $5@11.\nSweet potatoes, quiet; southern bas\nkets #1.25@1.75; Jersey 50@$2.50.\nDressed poultry, firm; turkeys 27@43;\nchickens 18@40; capons 27@44; fowls\n18@33; ducks 15@25; ducks, Long\nIsland 23@26. Live poultry, quiet;\ngeese 12@21; ducks 13\u00ae 23; fowls 29@\n32; turkeys 20 @30; roosters 18; chick\nens 22@34; broilers 25@34. Cheese\nquiet; state whole milk, fancy to\nspecial 24 @26; young America 22 @24.\nButter, market firmer; creamery ex\ntras 36; special market 36% @37.\nEggs, market quiet; nearby white\nfancy 42% @45; state whites 42% @45;\nfresh firsts 44 @44%; Pacific Coasts\n43@46; white Westerns 43% @44;\nnearby browns 46 48.\nINDIANAPOLIS LIVESTOCK\nINDIANAPOLIS, Jan. 18.\u2014Live\nstock for Wabash: Hog receipts 2.000:\nholdovers 681; market 25c higher,\nheavy higs. Over 300 lbs., S3.25@\n$9.60; 275-300 lbs., $9.60@$9$5; 250\n275 lbs., $9.90; medium hugs: 225-250\nlbs., $10.10; 200-25 lbs.. $10.25; light\nhoss: 180-200 lbs., $10.25; 160-180 lbs.,\n$10.25; light lights: 130-160 lbs., $10\u00ae\n$10.25; slaughter pigs: 90-130 lbs., $9\n@$9.75; packing sows, smooth, $8.50\n@$8.75; roughs, $8 @$8.50. Cattle re\nceipts, 200; calves, 200; market\nslaughter classes steady, vealers lower,\nvealers medium to choice, $13 @17;\ncull and common, $7@$13. Sheep re\nceipts 100; no test of market, quotably\nsteady.\nFORT WAYNE LIVESTOCK.\nFORT WAYNE, Ind., Jan. 18.\u2014No\nreceipts; hog market 15c up; 120 lbs.\ndown $9.25; 120-140 lbs. $9.50; 140\n160 lbs. 9.85; 160-200 lbs. $10; 200\n225 lbs. $9.90; 225-250 lbs. $9.75; 250\n300 lbs; $9.60; 300-3550 lbs. $9.45;\nroughs $7.75; stags $6; calvs $16.50;\nlambs $12.25,\n1\" y j\nBROAD STREET]\nMART COMMENT\nBy Harris, Upham and Co.\nMiddle-Western interests are opti\nmistic on Columbia Gas and Electric\nfor long pull, according to advices\nsent out from various sources. Com\npany is one of leaders in natural gas\nindustry \"with large reserves, trunk\nlines and distributing system. Gas\nrights are owned in more than 5,000,\n000 acres of land, about 85 per cent of\nwhich are held in reserve. Company\u2019s\npipe lines exceed 24,000 miles. It\nserves a large and profitable territory\nincluding Buffalo, Cincinnati, Cleve\nland, Columbus, Dayton and many\nother communities.\nConsolidated Gas for some time has\nbeen meeting excellent accumulation\nfrom interests credited with many\nmovements in stock during 1929. This\nbuying made itself felt on several oc\ncasions during past week, When it ad\nvanced sharply as an outside demand\ndeveloped.\nMost of activity and strength\nshown in Electric Power and Light\nduring past week has been result of\ndiscussion of development of natural\ngas activities by company. On basis\nof earnings stock is comparatively\nhigher than some other utilities, but\nspeculation in issue has been growing\n|and action has been attracting an\nj outside following.\nNew interests are said to have be\ncome active in United Aircraft, pre\nviously stock was under accumulation\nby important houses.\nb\nI\nBusiness Briefs\nBy Harris, Upham and Co.\nGeneral Motors acquires over 1,000,\n000 shares of its common at cost of\nabout $35,000,000 with intention of\nselling it to a second managers\u2019 se\ncurity company to be formed. Prob\nably managers security company will\nobtain funds through issuance of\nbonds.\na a a\nOklahoma City operators vote 75\nper cent oil curtailment. Meet with\npresident of Carter Oil, S. O. of New\nj Jersey, to consider revocation of\ncrude price cut.\na a a\nWholesale prices declined 1-5 of 1\nper cent in December compared with\nNovember and 2 1-2 per cent com\npared 'with December, 1928, according\nto Bureau of Labor Statistics.\na *a a\nFailures in past week numbered 638\nagainst 732 in preceding week and\ncomparing \u25a0with 583 in same week in\n1929, says Dun's Review.\na a a\nEvidences of business revival be\ncome more numerous, Dim\u2019s reports.\na a a\nWholesale and Jobbing trade and\nindustry moves forward cautiously j\nsays Bradstreet.\nana\nDouglas Aircraft Co. .year ended\nNov. 30 net profit $403,364 after\ncharges and taxes.\na a a\nProcter and Gamble in six months i\nended Dec. 31 earned $1.75 a share on j\n6,410,000 common shares. j\na a a\nPurity Bakeries in year ended Dec. j\n28 earned $7.02 a share on 805,062 j\ncommon shares against $5.99 on\n799,095 shares in preceding year.\na a a\nRediscount rate on Federal Reserve\nBank of San Francisco unchanged\nat 4 J2 per cent.\na a\nStandard Gas and Electric and\nsubsidiaries 12 months ended Nov. 30\ntotal income $76;171,731 after ex\npenses and ordinary taxes but before i\ndepreciation against $70,755,656 in;\nprevious 12 months.\nCHICAGO LIVESTOCK.\nCHICAGO, Jan. 18. Hogs\u2014Re-j\nceipts 7,000; market 10 to 15 lower.\nTop, $10.15; bulk, $9.50 @$10.10; heavy j\nweight, $9.35@$9.90; medium weight,1\n$9.65@$10.15; lightweight, $9.85@\n$10.15; light lights, $9.60@$10.10; j\npacking sows, $8.25 $9.10; pigs, $9.15 i\n@$10; holdovers 3,000.\nCattle\u2014Receipts 300; market steady i\nCalves\u2014Receipts 100; market steady; j\nbeef steers, good and choice, $14 @$15;\ncommon and medium, $10@$13.50; j\nyearlings, $10@$16; butcher cattle,:\nheifers, $8@$15; cows, $6.50@$10.50; i\nbulls, $8@$11; calves, $13.50@$17; j\nfeeder steers, $8.50 @$11; stocker steers j\n$8@$11; stocker cows and heifers, $6 j\n@$9.50.\nSheep\u2014Receipts 3,000; market stea\ndy. Medium and choice lambs, $13\n$13.90; culls and common, $11@$13;\nyearlings, $10.50 @$12; common and\nchoice ewes, $5@$7; feeder lambs. I\n$11.50 $13.\nEAST BUFFALO LIVESTOCK.\nEAST BUFFALO, Jan. 18.\u2014Hogs\u2014\nReceipts 800; holdovers 800; fairly ac\ntive to shippers, unevenly, but most\nly 25 35c over Friday\u2019s average; 110\n150 lbs. $10.90 @$11; 170-220 lbs. $10.75\n@$10.85; 230-250 lbs. $10.50@$10.65;\npacking sows $8.50 @$9.25.\nCattle\u2014Receipts 25; week\u2019s supply\nlight, quality improved 25 50c high\ner; early part of gain erased late.\nGood steers and yearlings $13.50\u00ae\n$14.50; bulk medium and shortfeds j\n$11.50@$13.25; common steers and!\nheifers $9.50@ $11.50; fat cows $9@ I\n$9.25; cutter grades $4.285@$6.50.\nCalver\u2014Receipts 50; vealers 50:\nhigher Monday, steady thereafter, $13\ndown.\nSheep\u2014Receipts 100; lambs, closing\n50c below opening and 25c under last\nweek; receipts moderate, good to\nchoice $13.75 @$14.25; week\u2019s top\n$14.90; medium and strong weights\n$12 25@$13.25; yearling wethers $12\u00ae\n$12.50; fat ewes $6@$7.25.\nCHICAGO PRODUCE.\nCHICAGO, Jan. 18.\u2014 Butter \u2014Re\nceipts 6,980 tubs; creamery extras\n35'-2; standards 35; extra firsts 34ft\n34*4; firsts 32@33; packing stock 16@\n20; specials 36@36ti.\nEggs\u2014Receipts 7,893