orted 170 to 200 lbs. 10.40;\ndesirable 120 to ISO lbs. 10.00?* 10.25;\n260 lbs. 10.00; bulk sows 8.00 to 8.25,\nstags 6.00 6.25. Cattle\u2014Receipts 275,\ncalves 75, cattle steady, vealers steady\nto lower, sales up to 17.00. Sheep. Re\nceipts 50. nominal.\nCLEVELAND PRODUCE.\nCLEVELAND. Jan. 18.\u2014Butter, ex\ntras 371-2; extra firsts 36?j361-2;\nseconds 28?* 29. Eggs, extras 411-2;\nfirsts 40. Poultry, fowls 28%30,\nmedium 25 27; leghorn 22 b 24;\nheavy spnngers 25 27; leghorn\nspringers 20; ducks 20 22; old cocks\n18; geese 15?}T7; Potatoes. Ohio and\nNew York $4.50 per 150 lb. sack;\nMaine Green Mt. $4.75 per 150 lb.\nsack; Idaho Russet, $4.25 per 100 lb.\nsack.\nCOTTON CLOSE.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 18.\u2014'The cotton\nmarket strengthened somewhat in the\nfinal hour of trading here today, and\nclosing prices were only 3 to 8 points\nlower. January closed at 17.17, March\n17.31, May 17.51, July 16.66, October\n17.64, December f7.74.\nCHILDREN\u2019S SLEEPERS\nMONDAY SPECIAL\nChildren\u2019s outing flannel sleeping\ngarments and pajamas, $1.00 kind,\nMonday special. 69c.\nBRANDON-DURRELL CO\nAdv. 19tl\ns\nWHEATADVANCES\nON ACTIVE BUYING\nRally Near Session\u2019*\nClose Boost.) Price\nof Grain.\nBy International New* Serricei\nCHICAGO, Jan. 18.\u2014Wheat dosed\n3-4 to 7-8 cent higher today with\nactive buying and short covering\nchiefly influenced by a closing rally\nof 11-8 to 2 cents at Winnipeg. Com\nwas up 3-8 to 1-2 cent and bats 1-8\nto 1-4 cent.\nCompared with a week ago, prices\nshowed net losses of 2 3-8 to 3 3-8\ncents for wheat; 1 3-8 to 2 1-2 cents\nfor com; 1 1-8 to 1 1-2 cents for oats i\nand 1 1-4 to 6 cents for rye.\nContinued slack export demand and\npronounced weakness at Winnipeg\nand Liverpool, were depressing foctors\nin wheat here. Liquidation of long\nwheat was extremely heavy during the\nweek while support was limited, es\npecially from outside sources. Crop\nnews from the domestic and Canadian i\nwheat belts was mixed.\nAnnouncement that the coopera\ntives representing the Federal Farm\nDoard here had advanced their baste\nprice limit 1 cents a bushel to $120 for\nNo. 1 hard and $1.18 for No. 2 hard\nled to a buying flurry here late in the\nweek.\nCom was forced to lower levels in\nsympathy with wheat, although the\nrun of news generally was bullish.\nWeather conditions over the belt were\ngenerally unfavorable for movement\nto market. Receipts were only moder-\nate here and country sales were light.\nLIVESTOCK REVIEW\nBy International New* Service I\nCHICAGO, Jan. 18.\u2014After ruling\nuneven during the week, hogs finished\nthe period 25 cents higher. Early in\nthe week prices were off sharply un\nder the influence of heavy recepits,\nbut a reaction followed later inspired\nby a smaller run, good demand from\nshippers and small packers. Receipts\nfor the week were 217,000 compared\nwith 222,000 last week and 264,000 a\nyear ago. Late top was $10.15 with\nthe bulk of all good hogs offered at\n$9.75 to $10. Fair to good heavy sold\nat $9.50 to $9.85.\nBulls and vealers were the only\nclasses of cattle to withstand the\ndownward price pressure this week.\nCompared with last week, steers sold\n50 to 75 cents lower; mixed yearlings\nand heifers 25 to 75 cents off; sows\nand cutters 25 cents lower. Bulls\ngained 15 to 25 cents and vealers 25\ncents. The best class of fat yearlings\nsold at $15 to $16 and poorer grades\nof steers ranged from $10 to $14. Cows\nand heifers sold at $6.50 to $14.\nCalves topped 'at $16.50. Receints of\ncattle for the week were 51,000 against\n48.000 last week and 54,000 a year ago.\nDemand for lambs was slack and\nreceipts heavy. Prices were from 25\ncents to $1 lower. Top for the week\nwas $14.50. Most of tire lambs sold\nat $13.20 to $14. Ewes finished at $5\nto $7.50. Arrivals for the week were\n89.000 compared with 68,000 last week\nand 69,000 a year ago.\nTOLEDO GRAIN.\nTOLEDO, Jam. 18.\u2014Wheat, No. 2\nred. 1.26\u00ab? 1.27. Com. No. 3 yellow,\n91l-2@ 92 1-2. Rye, No. 2, 1.02. Oats,\nNo. 2 white. 4957 50. Barfey, No. 2,\n71 Clover, domestic, cash, old, 10.95;\ncash. newr, 11.10; Jan. 11.10; February,\n11.15; February\u2019, choice. 11.55; Mar.,\n11.20; March, choice, 11.60. Imported,\ncash, old. 10.00. Timothy, cash, old,\n3.00; cash new. 3.25; Max. 3.40. Alsike,\ncash. 10.70; Feb. 10.75; Max. 10.90.\nButter, 35 @39. Eggs, 38639. Hay, t\ni.25 cwt. i\nCHICAGO CASH GRAIN.\nCHICAGO, Jan. 18.\u2014Wheat\u20143 red\n125; sample grade mixed 113. Com\u2014\n4 mixed 82\u2019 1-2@83 1-2; 5 mixed 82;\n3 mixed 78 1-2; 3 yellow 85 @86; 4\nyellow 82 1-2 @84 1-2; 5 yellow 815/\nB3; 6.yellow 78 l-2@80; 5 white 83 1-2;\n5 white 82; sample grade 77 1-2. Oats\n\u20142 white 46; 3 white 44\u00ae451-2. Rye\n\u2014none. Barley 61 @63.\nTry NEWS-TIMES Want Ad,\nSUIT\nOVERCOAT\n$55\nand up\nJOHN PARKER\n1151/2 N. Main St.\nPhone 3*6318\nThomson McKinnon\nNew York\n11 Wall St.\nChicago\n309 8. LaSalle St.\nIndianapolis\n41 N. Pennsylvania 8L\nToronto\n15 King St. West\nMEMBERS:\nNew York Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange 9\nNew York Coffee and Sugar Exchange\nNew York Produce Exchange\nNew York Curb Market\nChicago Board of Trade\nChicago Stock Exchange\nChicago Curb Exchange Assn.\nWinnepeg Grain Exchange\nAll Indianapolis Exchanges\nSOUTH BEND OFFICE\n301-306 J. M. S. Bldg.\nTelephone: Private Exchange 3-5137*\nOur private wires extend to the leading cities of the\nUnited States and Canada.\nFacts and Figures in connection with securities or com\nmodities cheerfully supplied.\nSpecial attention given grain and cotton futures.\nE. STANNARD, Manager","height":"31840","width":"23776"}}
